Aurora endpoints.

An Aurora cluster exposes several endpoints; they look like ordinary names, but each routes differently. The cluster, or writer, endpoint always points at the current primary, for writes. The reader endpoint load-balances across all the replicas, for reads. A custom endpoint points at a subset of instances you define. And an instance endpoint points at one specific instance, for debugging.

The application connects to the writer endpoint for writes and the reader endpoint for reads, and if the primary fails and a replica is promoted, both endpoints update automatically, so the application never has to know which instance is currently the writer. The reader endpoint round-robins across replicas, giving you a name-level load balancer for reads without managing one.

Custom endpoints are the lever for mixed workloads on one cluster, for example dedicating a couple of large replicas to overnight analytics through their own endpoint while the main reader endpoint serves everyday traffic from the smaller ones.
